h2. Steps to reproduce
 * Set up Confluence 6.6.7 with a SQL Server 2014 v12.0.5589 database (may affect other versions of SQL Server as well)
 * Populate the database with data with dimensions similar to this:
 ** Over 2 million rows in the content table
 ** At least one user with ~10,000 documents or versions of documents modified
 * Visit the recently worked on tab in the dashboard

h2. Expected results

Dashboard tab loads in a timely manner.
h2. Actual results

Dashboard tab never loads. The database CPU spikes for a long time and the query takes about 30 minutes to return. Due to the database being so busy this can cause stability issues causing the rest of Confluence to stop working as well.
h2. Workaround

The best workaround at the moment is to disable the feature. This involves 2 steps:
 # Modify your reverse proxy settings to block requests to the search endpoint when the any requests matching this pattern is issued:
{noformat}
/rest/api/content/search\?.*recentlyModifiedPagesAndBlogPostsByUser.*{noformat}
Unfortunately there is no way to do this within Tomcat or Confluence itself.
 # Add the following CSS to remove the link from the dashboard:
{code:java}
.confluence-dashboard li.nav-item-container-recently-worked {
    display: none;
}
{code}

Trying to apply the page numbering customisations mentioned in the [KB article|https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/customize-exports-to-pdf-190480945.html#CustomizeExportstoPDF-PageNumbering] will not work for DC instances that use the external process pool (sandbox) to export PDFs.

Specifically:
{code:java}
@page{    
  @bottom-center{        
  content: "Page " counter(page) " of " counter(pages);        
  font-family: ConfluenceInstalledFont, Helvetica, Arial, sans-  serif;        
  font-size: 8pt;    
  }
}
 
or
 
<span id="pageNum"/>
#pageNum:before { 
content: counter(page); 
}
{code}

Server customers and DC customers who have it disabled are not affected.
h2. How to Reproduce

1) Apply any of the above recommendations to add page numbering to PDF exports
2) Export a space as PDF
h2. Workarounds


None at the moment.

{panel:title=Atlassian Update - Oct 2020}
Hi All, I am one of the Product Managers on the Confluence Server/DC team. We do have Postgres 11 on our short term roadmap and are aiming to have it released within the next 6 months. We are also actively looking at support for Postgres 12 and 13. I apologise for the lack of visibility on this issue. We will add another update once we have an expected release version.
{panel}
PostgreSQL 11 was [released|https://www.postgresql.org/about/news/1894/] in October 2018. It would be desirable to have this supported to keep up to date with the latest PostgreSQL database versions.

h3. Problem description

Each Application Link in the system has customizable ServerName and generated ServerId. When a link to Jira issue is posted on the page, it automatically creates issue link in the following storage format

{code:none}
<ac:structured-macro ac:name="jira" ac:schema-version="1" ac:macro-id="638accfe-f49a-48c6-94dd-6923005b2ad8">
    <ac:parameter ac:name="server">Your Company JIRA</ac:parameter>
    <ac:parameter ac:name="serverId">986c17b5-1e77-3526-a338-fd866f770849</ac:parameter>
    <ac:parameter ac:name="key">MEOW-1</ac:parameter>
</ac:structured-macro>
{code}

On different Confluence installations the ServerId and ServerName might be different for the same external Jira. And after exporting and importing page content, the system might end up in the state when the page has issue link to some system that is not configured as an application link.

When such page is opened, there's an error macro placeholder in the place of issue links, which is logical because the system doesn't know anything about the external instance. But it also causes another problem, which is the subject of this issue. If you have correct issue link in the beginning of the page and then broken issue link somewhere in the middle, correct issue link will not work as well and display macro placeholder.

Please see the attached screenshot.

h3. Steps to reproduce
* create a page with two correctly set issue links in it
* go to database and change server id and server name for the second link to invalid values (alternatively you can import pages from another system with issue links to unknown Jira location)
* flush all caches
* refresh the page and check issue links

_Expected_: first normal issue link works as expected, while the second throws an error
_Actual_: both issues don't work

h3. How the problem should be fixed

The problem reproduces because Jira macro tries to resolve multiple issues in single batch. When it fails on invalid issue because can't find a server, it will also corrupt macro representation for correct one. This also explains why only the first application link was corrupted.

The problem happens in {{confluence-jira-plugin}}:
{code:java}
// Collect all possible server IDs from the macro definitions
for (MacroDefinition singleIssueMacroDefinition : singleIssueMacroDefinitions) {
    String key = singleIssueMacroDefinition.getParameter(JiraIssuesMacro.KEY);
    String serverId = getServerIdFromKey(singleIssueMacroDefinition.getParameters(), key, new DefaultConversionContext(entity.toPageContext()));

    if (serverId != null) {
        macroDefinitionByServer.put(serverId, singleIssueMacroDefinition);
    }
}
{code}

 If there's an issue link with invalid server info in the system, it shouldn't affect other correct issue links. This is not the case right now because of batch nature of confluence-jira-plugin. We need to add correct error handling.

h3. Workaround

The easiest way to fix broken links is to create application links to missing system. Luckily, when Jira macro resolves server information, it first tries to find application link with given ServerName and only in the case of failure fallbacks to ServerId. Because of this you can create application link with exactly the same name as you see in a page storage format parameter {{<ac:parameter ac:name="server">}} pointing to the correct Jira location.

If you try to access <somepage> with some hash (#) while logged out, you will be redirected to login:

{code:java}
http://localhost:3000/confluence/authenticate.action?destination=/somepage#somehash
{code}

However, the `destination` param does not encode the hash in the original URL - therefore it is not included in the redirect and the user is not redirected to the correct location after logging in.

